Package com.rb.nonbiz.collections

Class RBMapMergers

java.lang.Object
com.rb.nonbiz.collections.RBMapMergers
public class RBMapMergers
extends java.lang.Object
Various static utility methods that merge two or more RBMaps.

The various methods have different expectations about inputs. E.g. you may want to throw if there is ever any key appearing in more than one input RBMap.

    • mergeRBMapsAllowingOverlapOnSimilarItemsOnly

      public static <K,​ V> RBMap<K,​V> mergeRBMapsAllowingOverlapOnSimilarItemsOnly​(java.util.Iterator<RBMap<K,​V>> mapsIterator, java.util.function.BiPredicate<V,​V> itemsAreSimilar)
      Merges a bunch of maps into a single one. Throws if a key appears in more than one map, unless the items we are trying to insert are 'similar' (based on the predicate passed in). Since this similarity is not the same as equality, this means that if e.g. the first map maps "A" to money(100), the second one (in the iterator) maps "A" to money(100 + 1e-9), and the third one to money(100 - 1e-9), and similarity is 'values similar to an epsilon of 1e-8', then the resulting map will show money(100) in the final value for "A", NOT money(100 + 1e-9) or money(100 - 1e-9)

    • mergeRBMapsByValue

      @SafeVarargs public static <K,​ V> RBMap<K,​V> mergeRBMapsByValue​(java.util.function.BinaryOperator<V> mergeFunction, RBMap<K,​V> first, RBMap<K,​V> second, RBMap<K,​V>... rest)
      Merges a bunch of maps into a single one. In the event a key appears in more than one map, apply a binary operator (e.g. '+') to merge the values. This doesn't *assume* that the operator is commutative, but it probably should be. Otherwise, your result will depend on the order you pass the maps, which will be confusing.

    • mergeRBMapsByValue

      public static <K,​ V> RBMap<K,​V> mergeRBMapsByValue​(java.util.function.BinaryOperator<V> mergeFunction, java.util.function.UnaryOperator<V> onlyLeftPresent, java.util.function.UnaryOperator<V> onlyRightPresent, RBMap<K,​V> leftMap, RBMap<K,​V> rightMap)
      Merges two maps into a single one. For the 3 separate cases of a key appearing in the left map / right map / both maps, modify the values based on the functions passed in.

    • mergeRBMapsByTransformedValue

      public static <K,​ V1,​ V2> RBMap<K,​V2> mergeRBMapsByTransformedValue​(java.util.function.BiFunction<K,​java.util.List<V1>,​V2> mergeFunction, java.util.List<RBMap<K,​V1>> mapsList)
      Merges a bunch of maps into a single one. This is similar to the previous overload, except that it allows you to merge multiple (and possibly 0) items at a time, plus the value in the returned map doesn't have to be of the same type as the input maps. This is particularly useful for cases where it is more computationally expensive (or numerically unstable) to merge N items 2 at a time (as with the previous overload) vs. merging them all together.

    • mergeRBMapsByTransformedValue

      public static <K,​ V1,​ V2,​ V3> RBMap<K,​V3> mergeRBMapsByTransformedValue​(java.util.function.BiFunction<V1,​V2,​V3> mergeFunction, java.util.function.Function<V1,​V3> onlyLeftPresent, java.util.function.Function<V2,​V3> onlyRightPresent, RBMap<K,​V1> leftMap, RBMap<K,​V2> rightMap)
      Merges two maps into a single one, but also transforms the values into a possibly different type. For the 3 separate cases of a key appearing in the left map / right map / both maps, modify the values based on the functions passed in.
      See Also:

    • mergeRBMapsByValue

      public static <K,​ V> RBMap<K,​V> mergeRBMapsByValue​(java.util.function.BinaryOperator<V> mergeFunction, java.util.stream.Stream<RBMap<K,​V>> mapsStream)
      Merges a bunch of maps into a single one. In the event a key appears in more than one map, apply a binary operator (e.g. '+') to merge the values. This doesn't *assume* that the operator is commutative, but it probably should be. Otherwise, your result will depend on the order you pass the maps in the stream, which will be confusing.

    • dotProductOfRBMaps

      public static <K,​ V1 extends RBNumeric<? super V1>,​ V2 extends RBNumeric<? super V2>> double dotProductOfRBMaps​(RBMap<K,​V1> map1, RBMap<K,​V2> map2)
      For two maps of RBNumeric, multiply each corresponding item, and return the sum of those terms, kind of like a vector dot product. The keys are expected to be the same in each map.

    • mergeRBMapsInOrderAllowingOverwriting

      @SafeVarargs public static <K,​ V> RBMap<K,​V> mergeRBMapsInOrderAllowingOverwriting​(RBMap<K,​V> first, RBMap<K,​V> second, RBMap<K,​V>... rest)
      It is rare that we overwrite map entries, but sometimes we want to merge maps in the order they are supplied.

      This returns a map whose keys are the set union of the keys in the maps supplied, and corresponding value for every such key is the value for the latest map in the arguments supplied.
